function [MAC, MEAC, Density, ShortName, LongName] = PhotonAttenuation(Material, Energy)
% function [MAC, MEAC, Density, ShortName, LongName] = PhotonAttenuation(Material, Energy)
% Function providing the attenuation and energy absorption of x-ray and
% gamma-ray photons in various materials, based on NIST report 5632, by
% J. Hubbell and S.M. Seltzer.
%
% Input :
%   Material - atomic number in [1, 94] range,
%            - material index number in [95, 142] range
%            - symbol or name of the element
%            - cell array of any of above
%   Energy - single energy or vector of energies. For best results should
%            be in [0.001, 20] MeV range. Could be empty if you are only
%            interested in densities or names that are allowed.
% Output :
%   MAC  - Mass Attenuation Coefficients in cm^2/g
%   MEAC - Mass Energy-Absorption Coefficients in cm^2/g (not aviable for
%   elements 93 & 94)
%   Density - Density of Material in g/cm^3
%   ShortName, LongName - Name of Material (string). Two alternative names.
%
% History:
%   Written by Jarek Tuszynski (SAIC), 2006
% 	Inspired by John Schweppe Mathematica code avaiable at
% 	  http://library.wolfram.com/infocenter/MathSource/4267/
%
% References:
%   Tables are based on "X-Ray Attenuation and Absorption for Materials of
%   Dosimetric Interest" (XAAMDI) database:
% 	J. Hubbell and S.M. Seltzer, "Tables of X-Ray Mass Attenuation
% 	Coefficients and Mass Energy-Absorption Coefficients 1 keV to 20 MeV for
% 	Elements Z = 1 to 92 and 48 Additional Substances of Dosimetric Interest,"
% 	National Institute of Standards and Technology report NISTIR 5632 (1995).
% 	http://physics.nist.gov/PhysRefData/XrayMassCoef/cover.html
%
%   MAC values for elements 93 & 94 (Neptunium & Plutonium) came from
%   XCOM: Photon Cross Sections Database,
%   http://physics.nist.gov/PhysRefData/Xcom/Text/XCOM.html
%
% Details:
% 	The tables in NIST 5632 report give x-ray mass attenuation coefficients
% 	(MAC) and mass energy absorption coefficients (MEAC) for elements with
%   atomic number (Z) smaller than 92 (Uranium), and for 48 additional
% 	radiological materials. Photon energy range from 0.001 MeV to 20 MeV.
%
% 	The tables in NBSIR 87-3597 report give photon's "total attenuation
%   coefficients" for for elements with atomic number (Z) smaller than 100.
%   Photon energy range from 0.001 MeV to 100 GeV.
%
% 	The function covers the photon energy range from 0.001 MeV to 20 MeV.
% 	The values in the table are for room temperature and presure.
%   The values for ceric ammonium sulfate solution are for
% 	0.015 Molar solution.
%
% 	Interpolation is done using MATLAB's pchip function to log-log data of
%   coefficients as function of energy.
%
% Examples:
%   mac = PhotonAttenuation(1:94, exp(-6.9:0.01:2.99));
%   imagesc(log(mac))
%
%   [MAC, MEAC, Density, Name] = PhotonAttenuation('Pu', exp(-6.9:0.1:2.99))
%
%   [MAC, MEAC] = PhotonAttenuation(1:92, exp(-6.9:0.01:2.99));
